<p>Frustrated with getting measurements in tablespoons when you only have c=
ups? Or vice versa? If you=E2=80=99re baking, getting exact proportions is =
crucial to the success of your recipe. But you <em>can </em>convert accurat=
ely =E2=80=93 you just need to know the answer to the big questions: how ma=
ny tablespoons in a cup? </p>



<p>Whether you=E2=80=99re using metric or imperial, bookmark this and come =
back every time you need to convert cups to tablespoons, or the other way a=
round. Eventually you=E2=80=99ll be able to do it from memory!</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-full"><img fetchpriority=3D"high" deco=
ding=3D"async" width=3D"1024" height=3D"768" src=3D"https://whisk.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/08/cef430d6-ee23-4bcc-8cd1-ca0b0b518046.jpg" alt=3D"meas=
uring cups and spoon" class=3D"wp-image-10993"></figure>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-how-many-tablespoons-are-in-a-cup">H=
ow Many Tablespoons Are In A Cup?</h2>



<p><strong>Answer: One cup equals 16 tablespoons.</strong></p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">How much is there in a tbsp? </h3>



<p>A <strong>tablespoon</strong> (which is often abbreviated as =E2=80=9Ctb=
sp=E2=80=9D in recipes) is a common unit of measurement in cooking. It=E2=
=80=99s roughly equivalent to the amount of liquid a standard dinner spoon =
can hold or 3 teaspoons to be exact. But that doesn=E2=80=99t mean you shou=
ld just grab any old spoon!</p>



